to make pages.

02:28.409 --> 02:29.801
-Okay.
-All right, I'll see you.

02:29.845 --> 02:32.152
Good-bye, Mr. Diarrhea-head.

02:32.195 --> 02:34.154
-Hey, do you have my money,
Ruth? -[groans]

02:34.197 --> 02:35.416
Then we have nothing
to talk about.

02:35.459 --> 02:38.070
Aunt Jess, I have to pee.

02:38.114 --> 02:39.942
What? Oh, no.
We have to untangle you.

02:39.985 --> 02:41.378
Oh. We're not,
we're not gonna make it.

02:41.422 --> 02:42.771
I'll figure it out.

02:42.814 --> 02:44.729
Wait, wait, what does that mean?

02:44.773 --> 02:46.949
-Hey. -Hey, why is my baby
wrapped up in...

02:46.992 --> 02:48.037
never mind,
she'll figure it out.

02:48.080 --> 02:49.299
We just came back

02:49.343 --> 02:52.737
from Lillypads
and we need your help.

02:52.781 --> 02:54.130
SCHMIDT: We were picking up
our paperwork

02:54.174 --> 02:56.828
when we ran into that
supervillain/wax figure/

02:56.872 --> 02:59.831
former best friend of mine,
Benjamin.

02:59.875 --> 03:02.965
Have you gotten your kid
ready for this interview yet?

03:03.008 --> 03:04.532
We got ourselves
a 365 tutor, baby.

03:04.575 --> 03:06.969
Christmas, New Year's Eve,
Fourth of July,

03:07.012 --> 03:08.623
we own this man's ass.

03:08.666 --> 03:10.755
W-What are they
getting tested on?

03:10.799 --> 03:13.323
Draw a face. Cut a circle.
Know colors. Make eye contact.

03:13.367 --> 03:14.977
-SCHMIDT: I'm sorry, hold on.
-[Cece clears throat]

03:15.020 --> 03:16.283
I'm sorry, at three?

03:16.326 --> 03:18.459
-How could a child...
-[playing tuneful melody]

03:18.502 --> 03:20.243
Is that your boy over there
playing the piccolo?

03:21.505 --> 03:24.334
Oh, yeah.
That's my seed, all right.

03:24.378 --> 03:27.468
I had to lay down.
At which point, Benjamin's child

03:27.511 --> 03:29.121
started giving me shiatsu.

03:29.165 --> 03:30.297
-Oh.
-SCHMIDT: Which is apparently

03:30.340 --> 03:31.994
another thing
he knows how to do.

03:32.037 --> 03:34.823
-Ew. Preschool tutors? [scoffs]
-SCHMIDT: Okay, Jess,

03:34.866 --> 03:36.433
Ruth is never going to make it
through this interview

03:36.477 --> 03:39.480
without a professional tutor.
And if we look past the whole

03:39.523 --> 03:42.134
Banyon Canyon debacle,
that's you.

03:42.178 --> 03:44.441
Eh, I got out of that game
years ago.

03:44.485 --> 03:45.573
Look, I know it sounds crazy,

03:45.616 --> 03:47.575
but Lillypads
was really magical.

03:47.618 --> 03:51.100
The kids wear uniforms and,
you know, not to sound weird,

03:51.143 --> 03:53.581
-but they look hot.
-That sounds weird.

03:53.624 --> 03:55.452
-They did.
-I hear you, I hear you.

03:55.496 --> 03:57.280
They looked super hot.
Anyway, I have to run to work,

03:57.324 --> 03:59.064
so is there any chance
that you could, you know,

03:59.108 --> 04:01.458
teach her how to draw a face,
cut a circle,

04:01.502 --> 04:03.243
carry out a conversation...

04:03.286 --> 04:04.374
Okay, fine. I'll do it,
for Ruth.

04:04.418 --> 04:06.594
-Great. -Yes.
-Under one condition.

04:06.637 --> 04:08.900
-CECE: Sure.
-You do it on my terms.

04:08.944 --> 04:12.034
-What? -I'm gonna have to go
on a craft run, aren't I?

04:12.077 --> 04:13.818
I'm gonna need pipe cleaners,
glitter, glue,

04:13.862 --> 04:15.385
finger paints and six different
types of macaroni.

04:15.429 --> 04:17.126
And that's just
'cause I'm hungry.

04:17.169 --> 04:19.607
Honest to God, you don't
already have all of that

04:19.650 --> 04:22.479
in this room already?

04:22.523 --> 04:24.786
I mean...

04:26.091 --> 04:28.833
[sighs]

04:28.877 --> 04:31.227
Martini time.

04:31.271 --> 04:33.882
I like martinis.

04:37.538 --> 04:39.496
You know, I would be
back to writing

04:39.540 --> 04:42.325
because I'm kind of
in a nice flow, but, say,

04:42.369 --> 04:44.632
do you mind telling me
that really interesting story

04:44.675 --> 04:47.417
you just told me about when
you bought those shorts?

04:47.461 --> 04:49.158
I bought 'em.

04:49.201 --> 04:51.639
[laughs]
A-And from the start of it,

04:51.682 --> 04:53.293
when you realized
you needed new shorts?

04:53.336 --> 04:54.946
What was going on there?

04:54.990 --> 04:56.557
You just looked around your
house and there weren't shorts?

04:56.600 --> 04:58.080
Not the fingers, man,
I'm a writer.

04:58.123 --> 04:59.473
What are you doing here,
coming up on me like a maniac?

04:59.516 --> 05:00.822
Um, it's me, Winston.

05:00.865 --> 05:02.302
Sorry, man, I'm just
really edgy right now.

05:02.345 --> 05:03.651
-All right, man.
-Working on this thing

05:03.694 --> 05:05.696
-about Chicago, actually.
-Ooh.

05:05.740 --> 05:07.655
So you know it's gonna be raw.
You know it's gonna be personal.

05:07.698 --> 05:09.483
-Oh, yeah.
-Also, it doesn't exist.

05:09.526 --> 05:11.659
And if I don't have 20 pages
by 3:00 today,

05:11.702 --> 05:13.704
-I'm gonna get punched
in the face. -Who, your editor?

05:13.748 --> 05:15.532
No. Some guy I hired
off Craigslist.

05:15.576 --> 05:18.143
Wait, so you hired a man
to punch you in the face

05:18.187 --> 05:19.667
if you don't write 20 pages?

05:19.710 --> 05:21.669
Yeah. I have no idea
what he looks like, either.

05:21.712 --> 05:22.887
You know, I would have punched
you in the face for free.

05:22.931 --> 05:24.193
-Well, I got somebody.
-Okay.

05:24.236 --> 05:25.542
Well, anyway,
I have a real problem,

05:25.586 --> 05:27.109
one that I didn't bring
on myself.

05:27.152 --> 05:28.676
I'm just really slammed.

05:28.719 --> 05:30.939
So, I'm a detective now and I
have to testify in these trials.

05:30.982 --> 05:34.595
But you know I get rattled
on the stand.

05:34.638 --> 05:37.206
Can you repeat the question?

05:37.249 --> 05:40.078
I asked you if you'd like me
to repeat the question.

05:43.734 --> 05:45.475
Can you repeat the question?

05:50.611 --> 05:52.439
Can you have her
repeat the question?

05:52.482 --> 05:55.529
-Let's dig in.
-Thank you.

05:55.572 --> 05:57.139
When I was at law school,
I-I learned

05:57.182 --> 05:59.010
that if somebody falls apart
on the stand,

05:59.054 --> 06:00.708
it's mostly because
they're hiding something.

06:00.751 --> 06:02.492
So, I guess my question
to you, Detective, is:

06:02.536 --> 06:05.713
-what are you hiding?
-Nothing.

06:05.756 --> 06:07.932
-Nothing? [laughs]
-I have nothing to hide.

06:07.976 --> 06:10.195
Well, maybe not on this case,
but perhaps you're hiding

06:10.239 --> 06:13.547
something from... your past?

06:13.590 --> 06:15.331
Objection.
Form of a question.

06:15.375 --> 06:17.942
Withdrawn.
Isn't it true, Detective,

06:17.986 --> 06:19.640
that this could be the result
of a guilty conscience?

06:19.683 --> 06:21.163
I have nothing
to be guilty about.

06:21.206 --> 06:24.427
Ladies and gentlemen,
are we buying this?

06:24.471 --> 06:26.777
'Cause I'm not.

06:26.821 --> 06:30.259
My question is about the night
of January 12.

06:30.302 --> 06:32.000
-Wait, what? No, no, no. No, no.
-2001.

06:32.043 --> 06:34.350
Nick, that is a cold case and
I won't discuss it any further.

06:34.394 --> 06:35.656
Well, looks like
we're discussing it now.

06:35.699 --> 06:37.571
I was not masturbating!

06:39.050 --> 06:40.530
NICK:
Easy, Winston.

06:40.574 --> 06:42.271
You just screamed
"masturbating."

06:42.314 --> 06:44.186
-What are you doing, man?
-Sorry.

06:44.229 --> 06:48.016
[sighs] Okay.

06:48.059 --> 06:49.583
Jess, we have four hours.

06:49.626 --> 06:51.062
[Jess exhales]

06:51.106 --> 06:53.064
What are they doing?

06:53.108 --> 06:54.631
-[both exhale]
-What are they doing?

06:54.675 --> 06:55.676
What are they doing?
What are they doing?

06:55.719 --> 06:56.546
What are they doing? What
are they doing?

06:56.590 --> 06:58.200
What are, what are they doing?!

06:58.243 --> 06:59.419
We're practicing our breathing.

06:59.462 --> 07:00.768
Oh. Oh, okay, oh,

07:00.811 --> 07:02.247
well, good, wonderful.

07:02.291 --> 07:03.553
So, you're teaching Ruth
how to do the one thing

07:03.597 --> 07:05.425
she's known how to do
since birth.

07:05.468 --> 07:06.991
Do you want to get one
of your other teacher friends

07:07.035 --> 07:08.297
to prep your child for free?

07:08.340 --> 07:09.472
[whispering]:
I didn't think so.

07:09.516 --> 07:11.213
So shut your souphole.

07:11.256 --> 07:13.433
Oh, look, it's Happy Sock.

07:13.476 --> 07:16.000
-Hi, Happy Sock.
-Hi.

07:17.088 --> 07:18.612
JESS:
See, Schmidt?

07:18.655 --> 07:20.265
We're not cutting circles;
we're being circles.

07:20.309 --> 07:21.528
Right. Of course.

07:21.571 --> 07:23.007
Ruth can't hold a scissor,
but now she can

07:23.051 --> 07:25.749
twirl around like a goon
at a Phish show.

07:25.793 --> 07:28.535
Okay, well, now
you're just napping.

07:28.578 --> 07:31.625
We're not napping, we're going
on a brain exploration.

07:31.668 --> 07:33.104
I take that back, actually.

07:33.148 --> 07:34.454
Ruth is napping.

07:34.497 --> 07:36.238
Okay, well, that's enough, Jess.

07:36.281 --> 07:38.240
You're sending Ruth straight
to Triangles. You hear that?

07:38.283 --> 07:40.503
[mimics a chicken]
That's the schoolyard chickens.

07:40.547 --> 07:43.463
And they're...
and they're pecking at Ruth.

07:43.506 --> 07:44.464
And this time,
they want her eyes.

07:44.507 --> 07:46.857
I need my eyes for TV.

07:46.901 --> 07:48.685
Oh, honey, don't you worry
about a thing, okay?

07:48.729 --> 07:50.034
Daddy's gonna take over now.

07:50.078 --> 07:52.036
But the clock is a-ticking,

07:52.080 --> 07:53.037
so let's start with a drill.

07:53.081 --> 07:55.257
No. No drills.

07:55.300 --> 07:56.345
DRILL is an acronym.

07:56.388 --> 07:58.042
D: Do it. R: Redo it.

07:58.086 --> 07:59.479
I:
Imitate what you just did.

07:59.522 --> 08:00.828
L:
Learn to keep doing it.

08:00.871 --> 08:02.612
L: Live the rest of your life
doing it.

08:02.656 --> 08:04.048
DRILL, DRILL, DRILL.

08:04.092 --> 08:05.702
Technically, that's an acrostic.

08:05.746 --> 08:07.487
[high-pitched]:
Sweet burn, Jess.

08:07.530 --> 08:09.314
Yeah. You got me. DRILL.

08:12.230 --> 08:13.188
SCHMIDT:
And again.

08:13.231 --> 08:15.495
RUTH: Red, yellow, orange,

08:15.538 --> 08:17.279
-green.
-And that

08:17.322 --> 08:20.630
is how you earn a dollar
in America.

08:20.674 --> 08:22.632
[quietly]: She's not your child,
she's not your child...

08:22.676 --> 08:25.592
Okay, Ruth, we're gonna do the
colors one more time, and then,

08:25.635 --> 08:27.419
we're gonna move on to a section
that I like to call

08:27.463 --> 08:28.899
"Get the numbers right,
and Daddy will give you

08:28.943 --> 08:30.074
a stuffed animal."

08:30.118 --> 08:31.641
SCHMIDT:
Here we go.

08:31.685 --> 08:33.077
RUTH:
Red, yellow, orange,

08:33.121 --> 08:35.602
Denise.

08:35.645 --> 08:37.081
-Yes.
-SCHMIDT: I'm sorry. Uh...

08:37.125 --> 08:38.648
Did you just call green
"Denise"?

08:38.692 --> 08:41.651
Yes. The color's name is Denise.

08:41.695 --> 08:43.610
Well, I hope you're happy.
The interview is in an hour,

08:43.653 --> 08:45.481
and now green is Denise.

08:45.525 --> 08:47.744
Green is whatever
she wants it to be.

08:47.788 --> 08:49.311
[whispers]: Green is whatever
I want it to be.

08:49.354 --> 08:50.573
-Huh.
-JESS: Green could be Denise

08:50.617 --> 08:52.749
or Juanita or Jerry.

08:52.793 --> 08:54.751
I just realized...
[laughs]

08:54.795 --> 08:57.319
-...green is Jerry, for me.
-Green is not Jerry for me.

08:57.362 --> 09:00.322
Are you and Aunt Jess
in a fight?

09:00.365 --> 09:02.672
Oh, no, no, no.
Uh, we're just telling stories.

09:02.716 --> 09:04.892
Uh, once upon a time, there was
a fuzzy bunny who decided

09:04.935 --> 09:07.198
who decided that colors
didn't need names,

09:07.242 --> 09:08.678
and anything could be
called anything,

09:08.722 --> 09:10.550
and the world descended
into chaos.

09:10.593 --> 09:12.595
But the bunny was happy,
because the bunny wasn't forced

09:12.639 --> 09:15.511
-into somebody else's definition
of color. -Well, the fuzzy bunny

09:15.555 --> 09:17.165
wasn't really an authority,
now, was she?

09:17.208 --> 09:19.776
Because she used to work at a
school where instead of grades,

09:19.820 --> 09:21.125
they gave out rainbows.

09:21.169 --> 09:23.780
Bringing up the bunny's past
is uncalled for

09:23.824 --> 09:26.478
in this cabbage patch.
But the point is:

09:26.522 --> 09:30.178
I know about private schools,
and the whole system is corrupt.

09:30.221 --> 09:32.093
Said the very fuzzy bunny.

09:32.136 --> 09:35.357
Until the Jewish carrot farmer
brought down his mighty shovel.

09:35.400 --> 09:36.967
-The whole system is corrupt.
-[door closes]

09:37.011 --> 09:38.708
-What's going on?
-SCHMIDT: Your friend

09:38.752 --> 09:41.145
-is costing us Washington.
-Why didn't you marry Shivrang?

09:41.189 --> 09:43.583
Ruth, is that coffee?

09:43.626 --> 09:45.846
-Yep.
-Okay, there is a child here.

09:45.889 --> 09:47.195
I'm gonna take her
to the bedroom right now

09:47.238 --> 09:48.370
so she can watch
local news bloopers.

09:48.413 --> 09:50.459
I don't know why she likes them
so much.

09:50.502 --> 09:51.982
They're blowing their big shot.

09:52.026 --> 09:54.594
Okay. All right honey, let's go.

09:55.682 --> 09:56.944
Bye, honey.

09:56.987 --> 09:58.685
Mm-hmm. Talk to you later.

09:58.728 --> 10:00.164
Bye, Ruth. Great job.

10:00.208 --> 10:02.384
SCHMIDT:
Green is green.

10:02.427 --> 10:04.865
-You did this. You did this.
-You did this. You did this.

10:06.040 --> 10:08.564
-You did this.
-You did this.

10:08.608 --> 10:09.521
WINSTON:
Are we still on this?

10:09.565 --> 10:10.522
When are you gonna let this go?

10:10.566 --> 10:11.959
When you come clean, Detective.

10:12.002 --> 10:13.613
There is nothing
to come clean about.

10:13.656 --> 10:15.615
Wait, aren't you 11 pages away

10:15.658 --> 10:16.616
from getting punched
in the face?

10:16.659 --> 10:18.052
Oh, just answer the question.

10:18.095 --> 10:21.403
Does or does not the evidence
speak for itself?

10:21.446 --> 10:23.405
Do I need to refresh
your memory, sir?

10:23.448 --> 10:26.887
I didn't phone ahead
to warn you of my arrival.

10:26.930 --> 10:29.193
I just thought it would be fun
to surprise you at college.

10:29.237 --> 10:30.412
WINSTON:
It was fun.

10:30.455 --> 10:31.718
Well, it should have been fun.

